         <br>
      Safin Searches For Confidence After Latest Loss<br />
<br />
<br />
Photo By Susan Mullane By Tennis Week<br />
04/20/2005<br />
<br />
Marat Safin was present on court, but his confidence was MIA today. The top-seeded Safin tumbled out of Barcelona in a 6-4, 6-4 second-round setback to Jose Acasuso. Safin conceded his struggles to stroke shots between the lines are related to the ongoing confidence crisis between his ears.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Since capturing his second career Grand Slam at the Australian Open in January, Safin has failed to reach the quarterfinals in his last five tournaments, posting a 4-5 record in that spain. The losses have left Safin's confidence as cracked as one of his racquets after a collision with the court.<br />
<br />
"I've had a poor two months after Australia and it's very frustrating to be in this position," Safin said. "I've gradually lost all my confidence and that is why I lost today. My opponents know that I'm struggling and they obviously take advantage. I'm feeling a combination of frustration and pressure. I want to come back as fast as possible especially with the tournaments in Rome and Hamburg coming up, but there's no strategy to solve the problem it's just a question of running hard, fighting and waiting for my opportunity." <br />
<br />
The 2000 Barcelona champion, who was runner-up to Carlos Moya in 2003, dropped serve in the fifth game of the second set. Shortly after surrendering his serve, Safin began to lose his grip as the crowd began to back the Argentine. <br />
<br />
Safin, who spent most of his teenage years living and training in Valencia, was candid on the subject of the crowd response. <br />
<br />
"I wasn't angry with the crowd, they were angry with me," Safin said. "But if they don't like what I do then I won't come, the tournament can save some money and I can save some time and everyone will be happy." <br />
<br />
The 2002 Roland Garros semifinalist is searching for solutions that can only come with victories.<br />
<br />
"It's only a sport, so I don't want to get carried away about it," Safin said. "But it's clear that no one likes to be in this position. I'm experiencing a low at the moment, but it can only get better &#8212; when is the question though. If I continue fighting my opportunity will come and I'm sure that will be before French Open. Maybe I just need that little bit of luck to give me that extra push."</font></tt><p>
    </td>
  </tr>
